                    <p>The conversation around AI in business has been dominated by capability: what models can do, how fast they're improving, which workflows they can automate. That's a useful conversation. But in the final week of March 2026, two significant security incidents quietly reminded us that the infrastructure holding all of this AI capability together is still fragile, still under attack, and still being built with too much implicit trust. Neither incident made the front page. Both should have.</p>
                    <p>This is not a post about fear. It is about clarity — about what these two incidents actually reveal, why they matter to every business integrating AI, and what the organisations that will emerge from this era with their reputations intact are doing differently.</p>

                    <hr style="border-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.08); margin: 3rem 0;" />

                    <h2 id="sec-1">1. The Productivity Conversation We Are Not Having</h2>
                    <p>Spend twenty minutes reading about AI in business, and you will find the same story running through almost everything: capability, speed, automation, competitive advantage. These are real. The productivity gains from AI-assisted development, LLM integration, and agent-powered workflows are not theoretical; they are measurable, and the companies moving quickly on them are pulling ahead in ways that are already becoming difficult to catch up to.</p>
                    <p>But there is a second conversation that is happening much more quietly, and it matters just as much. It is the conversation about what happens when the infrastructure underpinning all of this AI capability is itself the target. About what it means to build on a stack that is evolving faster than most security teams can track. About the gap, widening every quarter, between the pace at which businesses are adopting AI tools and the pace at which they are governing them.</p>
                    <p>In the final week of March 2026, that conversation became unavoidable for anyone paying close attention. Two security incidents, within forty-eight hours of each other, made the case more clearly than any threat report or conference keynote could. One hit developers at the infrastructure level. The other hit patients at the data level. Together, they are not two bad weeks for two unlucky companies. They are a signal about where the threat landscape is moving, and who it is moving toward.</p>
                    <blockquote class="pull-quote">The organisations racing fastest to adopt AI are, in many cases, the same ones with the least visibility into what their AI infrastructure can actually access — and what happens when that access is abused.</blockquote>
                    <p>Understanding that signal, and what to do about it, is the purpose of this post.</p>

                    <hr style="border-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.08); margin: 3rem 0;" />

                    <h2 id="sec-2">2. Two Incidents That Reveal a Pattern, Not Just Bad Luck</h2>
                    <p>By now, you may have already seen the headlines: a backdoored Python library, a breached healthcare platform, credentials stolen at scale. The news moved fast. What the news coverage largely missed was the thread connecting the two incidents — the structural failure that sits underneath both of them and that will keep producing incidents like these until organisations address it directly.</p>
                    <p>Both attacks succeeded not because of technically sophisticated exploits or nation-state-grade zero-days. They succeeded because of trust that was assumed rather than examined. In the first case, a developer ecosystem that trusted package registries, trusted CI/CD pipelines, and trusted upstream security tools without verifying any of it. In the second, a healthcare architecture that trusted a perimeter, trusted that a single environment breach would be detected quickly, and trusted that the monitoring in place was adequate for the sensitivity of what it was protecting.</p>
                    <p>That is the pattern. Not two companies with bad security teams. Two organisations that made the same category of error that most organisations are currently making: treating trust as a given rather than as something that has to be earned, verified, and maintained at every layer of the stack.</p>
                    <blockquote class="pull-quote">The most dangerous assumption in modern software infrastructure is not "this will never be attacked." It is "this is probably fine." That quiet confidence, unexamined and unverified, is what both of these incidents exploited.</blockquote>
                    <p>It is also worth noting the timing. This week saw OpenAI close a record $122 billion funding round at an $852 billion valuation. Frontier models are dropping faster than ever. Agentic AI has moved from demonstration to production. The industry is moving at a pace that has never been seen before, and that pace is making the governance gap wider, not narrower, for most businesses. The incidents of March 2026 are what that gap looks like when it is found and exploited.</p>

                    <hr style="border-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.08); margin: 3rem 0;" />

                    <h2 id="sec-3">3. Breach #1: The LiteLLM Supply Chain Attack</h2>

                    <h3>What LiteLLM Actually Is</h3>
                    <p>To understand why this attack matters, you need to understand what LiteLLM does. It is a universal routing layer for large language model APIs — a single interface that lets developers call models from OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, AWS Bedrock, and over a hundred other providers without rewriting their integration logic for each one. It handles authentication. It manages retries. It tracks costs across providers. In most modern AI stacks, it sits directly between your application and every LLM API call you make. It had approximately 97 million monthly downloads and was used by companies including Stripe, Netflix, and Google.</p>
                    <p>That position — that concentrated, trusted access to API credentials across every AI service an organisation uses — is precisely what made it an attractive target. Compromise LiteLLM on a developer machine, and you do not just steal one credential. You potentially harvest the keys to every AI service that organisation is running and paying for.</p>

                    <h3>How the Attack Unfolded</h3>
                    <p>The attacker group, known as TeamPCP, did not start with LiteLLM. They started in late February by exploiting a misconfigured GitHub Actions workflow in Aqua Security's Trivy scanner, a widely trusted open-source vulnerability tool. They then used the access harvested from Trivy to attack Checkmarx KICS on March 21. By March 24, they had used the same infrastructure to exfiltrate PyPI publishing credentials from LiteLLM's own CI/CD pipeline, which was itself using Trivy as part of its build process.</p>
                    <p>The progression is not accidental. Security tools. Infrastructure libraries. AI proxies. TeamPCP is specifically targeting the tools developers trust most deeply, because that trust translates directly into the highest-value access. Every step of their campaign used the trust established in the previous one.</p>

                    <h3>What the Malware Did</h3>
                    <p>Version 1.82.8 contained a <code>.pth</code> file that Python executes automatically on every interpreter startup, with no import statement needed. Opening a terminal triggered it. Running tests triggered it. Starting a server triggered it. Spinning up a CI runner triggered it.</p>
                    <p>The payload harvested SSH private keys, <code>.env</code> files containing API keys and secrets, cloud credentials across AWS, GCP, and Azure, Kubernetes service account tokens and cluster configs, and database passwords — everything encrypted and exfiltrated to a domain crafted to look like legitimate LiteLLM infrastructure. On Kubernetes environments, the attack escalated further: deploying privileged pods and reading cluster-wide secrets.</p>
                    <p>A bug in the malware — a recursive fork bomb caused by the <code>.pth</code> launcher — spawned child processes that re-triggered themselves, causing some machines to crash from RAM exhaustion. That crash is how the breach was first noticed. A developer at FutureSearch saw the anomaly, used Claude Code to trace it, and identified the backdoor. Without that accidental signal, the credential theft would have continued silently.</p>

