                    <h3>The Structural Lesson</h3>
                    <p>The LiteLLM attack is a case study in cascading trust failure. LiteLLM trusted Trivy. Trivy had been compromised. Developers trusted PyPI. Teams trusted unpinned builds to pull a safe version. Every assumption in that chain was reasonable in isolation. None of them were verified. One upstream compromise collapsed them all.</p>
                    <p>Over 74% of malicious packages reach production through transitive dependencies — packages that your packages install, not packages you consciously chose. Most teams audit their direct dependencies. Almost none audit the full chain. The LiteLLM attack is a live demonstration of what that gap costs.</p>

                    <hr style="border-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.08); margin: 3rem 0;" />

                    <h2 id="sec-4">4. Breach #2: The CareCloud EHR Hack</h2>

                    <h3>Who CareCloud Is</h3>
                    <p>CareCloud is a publicly traded healthcare technology company serving over 40,000 medical practices, clinics, and hospitals across all 50 US states. Its platform handles electronic health records, practice management, billing, revenue cycle management, and clinical analytics across more than 70 medical specialties. It is, in practical terms, the software infrastructure for a significant slice of American healthcare delivery.</p>

                    <h3>What Happened</h3>
                    <p>On March 16, 2026, an attacker gained unauthorised access to one of CareCloud's six electronic health record environments. The company restored full functionality the same day. But by then, the attacker had been inside a live healthcare data environment for approximately eight hours, undetected.</p>
                    <p>CareCloud did not publicly disclose the incident until March 30 — fourteen days after the breach — after determining it was legally material enough to require SEC notification. Within 24 hours of the public disclosure, multiple law firms had opened class action investigations. The forensic investigation into what was accessed or exfiltrated remains ongoing.</p>

                    <h3>Why Eight Hours Matters</h3>
                    <p>A typical electronic health record contains a patient's full name, date of birth, address, Social Security number, diagnoses, prescription history, insurance details, and clinical notes from every appointment. In illicit data markets, healthcare records consistently command higher prices than financial credentials — harder to change than a password, more comprehensive as an identity document, and more useful for a wider range of fraud.</p>
                    <p>The eight-hour window is only part of the concern. The architecture that allowed a single environment breach to potentially threaten records across 40,000 providers raises deeper questions that the breach itself did not create — only exposed. What data minimisation had been applied? How long had records been retained? Was the environment segmented in a way that limited blast radius, or only in a way that limited entry points?</p>

                    <h3>Healthcare as a Proxy for What Comes Next</h3>
                    <p>Healthcare is the most attacked sector in the United States, and it is worth understanding why. It sits at the intersection of three conditions: extraordinarily sensitive data, operational systems that cannot afford downtime, and chronic underinvestment in security relative to the value of what is being protected. Those conditions exist, in varying degrees, across every industry that is now integrating AI at speed. Healthcare is simply further along the exposure curve. What is happening there now is a preview of what will happen elsewhere as AI integration deepens and the data held by AI-adjacent systems grows.</p>

